BLACK MESA PORTAL DEVICE, HELLO AGAIN, WE'RE FROM THE FUTURE


Sam, I'm beginning to suspect the universe has decided that one trip through the Resonance Cascade isn't enough for you. Now it's carefully teleporting us back in time with the enviable persistence of a serial stalker.

The reason? The portal we activated in the future apparently decided it was bored of working on a schedule and yanked us here. To Black Mesa. To another part of it. In the midst of that very experiment we already... well, you get the idea.

We're greeted by a local marvel of engineering - the "Portal Device." A machine built to open passages between worlds without the risk of a personal visit. So, someone smart decided that sending people to Xen was a bad idea and built a machine to fetch samples itself. Sounds reasonable. Probably until a guy in bloodied armor stumbles into the control room, looking like he's seen the end of the world and wasn't happy about it.

A scientist is at the controls. Nervous, focused, with a glint in his eye, like someone about to either make a breakthrough or accidentally burn down the lab. He looks at us and... lo and behold. He mistakes you for "Ivan the Space Biker". Who is that, I ask? I have no idea, Sam. But this Ivan, apparently, was supposed to come in clean-shaven and conduct the experiment. Our scientist is a little taken aback by your clean-shaven look. Apparently, he imagines a Space Biker as a bearded, seasoned man, and here... well, you.

The parameters are unstable. Sam, I've heard that before. Last time, these words ended with us punching a hole between dimensions, bringing in the Nihilanth, and setting up a Xen facility in Black Mesa. Now we have a chance to do it all again. Or do it differently. But judging by the fact that we're here, and the scientist is already calling us to the installation... the chances of "doing it differently" are slim.

Recommendation: play along. You are Ivan Space Biker, shaved, laconic, slightly perplexed by the fact that you've ended up in a time machine. Approach the device, look around, pretend you understand what's happening. And remember: transferring a sample through a portal is always a risk. And risk, as played by Sam Stone, is a guaranteed explosion. It's just a matter of scale.

We were yanked from the future to trigger the past. The irony of fate deserves its own nomination. Let's play the part. Who knows, maybe this time there won't be a resonance cascade.

Although... it looks like it has already arrived...
